WEBVTT

00:02.636 --> 00:05.504
<i> (Gordon)</i>
<i> I'm visiting an inn</i>
<i> in Massachusetts</i>

00:05.539 --> 00:07.706
<i> that's being run</i>
<i> by a dysfunctional couple.</i>

00:07.742 --> 00:10.676
[crying]
I love you so much, but you suck
as a business partner.

00:10.711 --> 00:12.211
<i> (Gordon)</i>
<i> He's lost...</i>

00:12.246 --> 00:13.512
I have no idea
what I'm doing here.

00:13.547 --> 00:14.680
<i> (Gordon)</i>
<i> And she's lost it.</i>

00:14.715 --> 00:16.215
[sobs]

00:16.250 --> 00:18.183
Just wanted
to keep it together tonight.

00:18.219 --> 00:19.818
<i> (Gordon)</i>
<i>And with the staff suffering</i>
<i> as well...</i>

00:19.854 --> 00:21.220
What's the worst thing
she's ever done to you?

00:21.255 --> 00:23.422
Smacked me
on the back of the head.

00:23.457 --> 00:24.690
<i> (Gordon)</i>
<i> I'm not even sure</i>
<i>if I can get through to them.</i>

00:24.725 --> 00:26.959
<i>The whole operation is screwed.</i>

00:26.994 --> 00:28.227
What do you think we should do?

00:28.262 --> 00:30.229
- Close.
- Have a nice night.

00:37.805 --> 00:39.905
<i> (Gordon)</i>
<i> Nestled in the heart</i>
<i> of scenic New England</i>

00:39.940 --> 00:43.442
<i>lies the small industrial town</i>
<i>of Southbridge, Massachusetts.</i>

00:45.513 --> 00:47.980
<i> It's home to</i>
<i>the Vienna Inn and Restaurant.</i>

00:48.015 --> 00:50.516
<i> Husband and wife,</i>
<i> Jonathan and Lisa Krach,</i>

00:50.551 --> 00:52.584
<i> have owned</i>
<i> and operated the inn</i>

00:52.620 --> 00:55.054
<i> since buying the property</i>
<i> back in the year 2000.</i>

00:55.089 --> 00:57.956
<i> (Lisa)</i>
<i>Jonathan had this crazy idea</i>

00:57.992 --> 01:00.325
of creating the Vienna

01:00.361 --> 01:03.829
as an Austrian restaurant
and bed-and-breakfast.

01:03.864 --> 01:06.632
She said,
"Have you been drinking?

01:06.667 --> 01:09.468
I said, "No, not yet."
[chuckles]

01:09.503 --> 01:13.505
<i> (Lisa)</i>
<i> We try to transport people</i>
<i>and to give them that feeling</i>

01:13.541 --> 01:16.542
of being in Vienna
without having to fly there.

01:19.847 --> 01:22.581
<i> (David)</i>
<i>When people come in and they</i>
<i>stay here for the first time,</i>

01:22.616 --> 01:24.550
they think that Jonathan and
Lisa are very gracious hosts,

01:24.585 --> 01:27.286
<i> charming,</i>
<i> the perfect married couple.</i>

01:27.321 --> 01:29.455
<i> but if you dig</i>
<i> a little bit deeper</i>

01:29.490 --> 01:31.523
<i> and you stay</i>
<i> a little bit longer,</i>

01:31.559 --> 01:33.058
you find out
it's quite a different story.

01:33.094 --> 01:34.660
<i> (Melissa)</i>
<i>Lisa is an emotional person.</i>

01:34.695 --> 01:36.328
<i> She does get upset often.</i>

01:36.363 --> 01:38.430
<i> She will just,</i>
<i> you know, explode</i>

01:38.466 --> 01:41.400
and she can't help
but be upset.

01:41.435 --> 01:42.601
<i> She's over the top.</i>

01:42.636 --> 01:44.403
[snaps belt]

01:44.438 --> 01:47.706
<i> (Jonathan)</i>
<i> My beautiful wife, my boss,</i>

01:47.741 --> 01:49.975
sometimes
she's not so nice to me.

01:50.010 --> 01:53.812
Why do you always have to dress
like a [bleep], like, dumb?

01:53.848 --> 01:55.881
There has been a time where
I called her a "psycho {bleep}"

01:55.916 --> 01:57.416
'cause she was being
a psycho {bleep}.

01:57.451 --> 02:00.586
Clean up, man.
I'm done with this.

02:00.621 --> 02:02.621
<i> (Jessica)</i>
<i> I don't feel</i>
<i> like Lisa's authentic.</i>

02:02.656 --> 02:05.691
When she's crying, I don't
feel like she ever means it.

02:05.726 --> 02:08.527
[sobbing]

02:09.964 --> 02:12.831
Jonathan and Lisa
live in a room at the inn.

02:12.867 --> 02:14.500
<i> You can hear them</i>
<i> screaming at each other.</i>

02:14.535 --> 02:15.667
<i> You can hear it</i>
<i> in the dining room.</i>

02:15.703 --> 02:17.636
<i> So there's no boundaries.</i>

02:17.671 --> 02:19.471
<i> They'll come down after the</i>
<i>shift at the end of the night,</i>

02:19.507 --> 02:22.007
<i> and they'll have cigars,</i>
<i> have some drinks.</i>

02:22.042 --> 02:24.343
The environment can quickly
become unprofessional.

02:24.378 --> 02:25.711
She'll go up to a table

02:25.746 --> 02:26.879
and ask them about,
like, their sex lives.

02:26.914 --> 02:28.914
You are good-looking.

02:28.949 --> 02:31.049
<i> (David)</i>
<i>We don't get that many locals</i>
<i> at the Vienna.</i>

02:31.085 --> 02:32.951
There's, like, a lot of things

02:32.987 --> 02:35.120
that people think in town
about the Vienna,

02:35.156 --> 02:38.590
<i> and I think it's become</i>
<i> a little taboo.</i>

02:38.626 --> 02:40.592
<i> (Lisa)</i>
<i> You have those rumors</i>
<i> going around.</i>

02:40.628 --> 02:42.461
<i> People say,</i>
<i> "Ooh, the Vienna.</i>

02:42.496 --> 02:44.663
<i> They're all swingers.</i>
<i> It's a big brothel."</i>

02:44.698 --> 02:46.899
<i> It's just--</i>
<i> it's just ridiculous.</i>

02:46.934 --> 02:49.535
It's ridiculous.

02:49.570 --> 02:52.504
That being said,
we're very friendly people...

02:52.540 --> 02:55.073
very friendly.

02:58.112 --> 03:00.879
<i> (David)</i>
<i>People from the outside think</i>
<i>the Vienna's doing very well</i>

03:00.915 --> 03:02.648
<i> and we're very prosperous,</i>

03:02.683 --> 03:05.350
but somewhere in there,
we're losing.

03:05.386 --> 03:06.718
<i> (Melissa)</i>
<i> They're dragging us down</i>
<i> with them,</i>

03:06.754 --> 03:08.654
<i> and if they want us</i>
<i> to help them,</i>

03:08.689 --> 03:11.590
they--they need to help us.

03:11.625 --> 03:13.392
<i> (Jonathan)</i>
<i> The Vienna is our home,</i>

03:13.427 --> 03:16.395
<i> has been for 13-plus years.</i>

03:16.430 --> 03:19.164
And, you know,
it's hanging by a thread.

03:19.200 --> 03:22.167
<i> [somber music]</i>

03:22.203 --> 03:25.103
<i> ¶ ¶</i>

03:25.139 --> 03:28.106
<i> [upbeat music]</i>

03:28.142 --> 03:32.544
<i> ¶ ¶</i>

03:32.580 --> 03:34.713
And this,
5:30 at table five.

03:38.852 --> 03:41.486
Look at this place.
My God.

03:41.522 --> 03:44.556
What happened to him?

03:44.592 --> 03:46.692
He didn't last very long,
did he?

03:46.727 --> 03:48.060
<i> (Jonathan)</i>
<i> He found our cat.</i>

03:48.095 --> 03:50.028
[laughter]

03:50.064 --> 03:51.997
Well, bloody hell.

03:52.032 --> 03:53.599
Dead cat and a cabbage.

03:53.634 --> 03:56.468
Isn't that funny?

03:56.503 --> 03:58.103
- Good morning.
- Hello, welcome.

03:58.138 --> 04:00.205
- Nice to meet you.
- Likewise, good to see you too.

04:00.241 --> 04:01.506
Gordon.
First name is?

04:01.542 --> 04:02.741
- Melissa.
- Melissa.

04:02.776 --> 04:03.875
(Lisa)
Good morning.

04:03.911 --> 04:05.110
- How are you?
- How are you?

04:05.145 --> 04:06.578
- Lisa Krach.
- Lisa, nice to see you.

04:06.614 --> 04:08.814
- You don't look very happy.
- I do.

04:08.849 --> 04:10.682
- It's my resting face.
- Oh, this is your happy face?

04:10.718 --> 04:12.818
- Well, um...
- Yes, welcome to the Vienna.

04:12.853 --> 04:13.952
So happy to be here.

04:13.988 --> 04:15.520
What happened to the cat?

04:15.556 --> 04:17.122
- [chuckles]
- Poor thing.

04:17.157 --> 04:18.557
(Lisa)
Cat got run over.

04:18.592 --> 04:20.559
Oh, I see.
And you got it stuffed?

04:20.594 --> 04:22.761
- For Halloween.
- Right.

04:22.796 --> 04:25.797
Actually,
better to see you now.

04:25.833 --> 04:28.000
Right, um, yeah.

04:28.035 --> 04:29.801
Uh, love the attire,
by the way.

04:29.837 --> 04:31.703
Thank you.

04:31.739 --> 04:33.105
(Melissa)
Everyone wears this.

04:33.140 --> 04:34.940
Well, how much are the outfits?

04:34.975 --> 04:36.608
About $300, $400.

04:36.644 --> 04:37.976
- $300?
- $300.

04:38.012 --> 04:38.977
Average, you know.

04:39.013 --> 04:40.512
They get their own.

04:40.547 --> 04:41.580
I mean, they're
their own dresses, you know?

04:41.615 --> 04:42.748
Oh, you buy your own uniforms?

04:42.783 --> 04:43.782
- Yes.
- Yes, they do.

04:43.817 --> 04:45.117
- Stop it.
- We do.

04:45.152 --> 04:46.652
Well, they have 'em
for many years.

04:46.687 --> 04:48.253
And it reminds them
to not gain weight.

04:48.289 --> 04:50.722
[chuckles]

04:50.758 --> 04:52.557
(Gordon)
Wow, so who designed the place?

04:52.593 --> 04:54.593
Well, uh, my husband and I.

04:54.628 --> 04:55.994
And whose idea
was it to buy it?

04:56.030 --> 04:57.996
Uh, my husband.

04:58.032 --> 05:00.098
- So it wasn't yours?
- It was not my idea.

05:00.134 --> 05:01.833
I was actually
very much against it.

05:01.869 --> 05:03.068
Wow.

05:03.103 --> 05:04.503
Why were you against it?

05:04.538 --> 05:05.771
It was very overwhelming.

05:05.806 --> 05:07.539
I had two small children.

05:07.574 --> 05:11.643
Probably, uh, after I lost
my mind the first year...

05:11.679 --> 05:13.645
I think we started
to get a hang of it.

05:13.681 --> 05:15.047
And who's Austrian?
Are you from--

05:15.082 --> 05:16.815
My husband's half-Austrian
and Polish.

05:16.850 --> 05:18.917
- Right.
- I'm not nearly as exotic.

05:18.952 --> 05:20.085
I'm very American.

05:20.120 --> 05:21.753
- Right,
and he's the chef, right?

05:21.789 --> 05:24.156
So he runs the restaurant,
kitchen, and you run the inn.

05:24.191 --> 05:25.691
Correct.

05:25.726 --> 05:27.693
And whose idea
was the violins on the table?

05:27.728 --> 05:29.561
<i> - Mine.</i>
<i> - Where'd that come from?</i>

05:29.596 --> 05:32.097
That was actually from
an estate sale down the street.

05:32.132 --> 05:33.699
A dead man's violin?

05:33.734 --> 05:35.801
- No, no.
- Yeah, why not?

05:35.836 --> 05:38.003
I don't want to sit
across a table with my wife

05:38.038 --> 05:39.738
and look
at a dead man's violin.

05:39.773 --> 05:41.206
- Well--
- Bit freaky, no?

05:41.241 --> 05:42.674
I don't know.
What would you rather look at

05:42.710 --> 05:43.909
when you see the Vienna?

05:43.944 --> 05:46.211
- Her.
- Who's "her"?

05:46.246 --> 05:48.146
- My wife.
- Oh, your wife, yes.

05:48.182 --> 05:52.351
But you have to have something
to make up that white space.

05:52.386 --> 05:55.320
- What would you suggest?
- My wife.

05:55.356 --> 05:57.055
[chuckles]
You gonna put her on the table?

05:57.091 --> 05:58.357
That's kind of scandalous.

05:58.392 --> 06:00.258
I am so [bleep] confused.

06:00.294 --> 06:02.027
<i> Dead man's violin.</i>

06:02.062 --> 06:03.895
What about some flowers?

06:03.931 --> 06:07.566
Bloody hell, is this place
always as clustered as this?

06:09.937 --> 06:11.937
- And who's that there?
- A Prussian family, of course.

06:11.972 --> 06:13.805
That was, uh, Friedrich,

06:13.841 --> 06:16.641
that their family
all was murdered--

06:16.677 --> 06:18.076
- Murdered?
- Yes.

06:18.112 --> 06:20.712
Wow. So dead man's violin
and murder on the wall.

06:20.748 --> 06:24.249
Great story to encourage
a nice, warm, welcoming dinner.

06:24.284 --> 06:27.152
So why don't
I check in upstairs?

06:27.187 --> 06:28.620
You can do that right now.

06:28.655 --> 06:29.921
- Yes, please.
- Okay.

06:29.957 --> 06:31.156
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

06:31.191 --> 06:33.859
Wow.
[shudders]

06:33.894 --> 06:35.727
Wow.

06:35.763 --> 06:38.330
<i> Interesting indeed.</i>
<i> Just a clutter.</i>

06:38.365 --> 06:39.998
- Your bedroom's over here.
- Rocking chair?

06:40.033 --> 06:41.633
Where's that from?

06:41.668 --> 06:43.368
That's actually the first piece
I ever refinished.

06:43.404 --> 06:44.936
Wow.

06:44.972 --> 06:47.139
So you're quite
an antiques hoarder.

06:47.174 --> 06:48.907
[knock at door]
- Room service.

06:48.942 --> 06:51.309
Oh, room service.
Come in.

06:51.345 --> 06:52.911
Holy mackerel.

06:52.946 --> 06:54.279
Now, what we have here
is some pulled boar.

06:54.314 --> 06:56.081
- Shredded. Shredded.
- Oh, pulled. Right.

06:56.116 --> 06:58.683
And then you have a little
celery root right on top.

06:58.719 --> 07:00.185
Wow.
And what's that?

07:00.220 --> 07:01.186
(Lisa)
It's a little parsley.

07:01.221 --> 07:05.090
Excellent.
Um...

07:05.125 --> 07:07.025
- Take one.
- Would you like me to have one?

07:07.060 --> 07:08.860
Yeah, of course.
There's three pieces.

07:08.896 --> 07:10.228
- Okay.
- Excellent.

07:10.264 --> 07:11.930
- Sure.
- Thank you.

07:11.965 --> 07:13.698
- Thank you for sharing.
- You're welcome.

07:13.734 --> 07:15.200
Hold on.
Wait, wait.

07:15.235 --> 07:17.035
Let me put a little bit
of the garnish on there--

07:17.070 --> 07:18.403
You want me to have that?

07:18.439 --> 07:21.006
Yeah, we'll have
a little piece each.

07:29.650 --> 07:31.917
What did you think of that,
by the way?

07:31.952 --> 07:34.352
Celery root--
really don't like it.

07:34.388 --> 07:37.422
The pulled boar--
maybe just a bit more salt.

07:37.458 --> 07:39.157
Wow. And what did you
think of that?

07:39.193 --> 07:40.992
I think it's a nice little
surprise for people

07:41.028 --> 07:44.329
when they come in
to liven up their appetite.

07:44.364 --> 07:46.131
Boar was very watery.

07:46.166 --> 07:47.833
It was very watery.
I did notice that.

07:47.868 --> 07:49.935
And the bread was soggy,
soaking wet.

07:49.970 --> 07:51.403
From the celery root.

07:51.438 --> 07:53.405
- Thank you.
- Enjoy your stay.

07:53.440 --> 07:55.474
Please pass on my comments
to the chef.

07:55.509 --> 07:57.209
I definitely will.

07:58.745 --> 07:59.878
Here we go.

08:02.015 --> 08:03.048
<i> (Gordon)</i>
<i> Oh, dear.</i>

08:03.083 --> 08:04.282
<i> Okay.</i>
<i> Wow.</i>

08:04.318 --> 08:05.784
And who designed
these bedrooms?

08:05.819 --> 08:07.419
I designed everything.

08:07.454 --> 08:08.854
You designed?

08:08.889 --> 08:11.122
Mm-hmm.
I wallpapered it as well.

08:11.158 --> 08:12.757
Seriously?

08:12.793 --> 08:14.226
What's this?

08:14.261 --> 08:15.961
That's another closet.

08:15.996 --> 08:17.295
What do you mean,
another closet?

08:17.331 --> 08:18.730
I don't have a closet
in my bedroom.

08:18.765 --> 08:20.265
That's the closet that we have

08:20.300 --> 08:22.801
because there's an area
over here for guests to use.

08:22.836 --> 08:24.803
But where am I gonna hang
my clothes?

08:24.838 --> 08:26.137
Right over here.

08:28.909 --> 08:32.077
But...

08:32.112 --> 08:33.411
You don't need
an entire closet.

08:33.447 --> 08:35.914
So if you need clothes
out of your closet--

08:35.949 --> 08:37.349
I have to plan ahead.

08:37.384 --> 08:38.884
Do you have the key on you?

08:38.919 --> 08:40.085
I do.

08:40.120 --> 08:41.520
Can I see inside?
I just--

08:41.555 --> 08:43.221
I'm a bit freaked with
locked doors in my bedroom.

08:43.257 --> 08:45.056
- Gosh.
- Yeah, I'm sorry.

08:45.092 --> 08:46.491
- It's okay.
- Thank you.

08:46.527 --> 08:48.260
- It's right here.
- Oh, it's there?

08:48.295 --> 08:50.996
Wow.

08:51.031 --> 08:53.331
[chuckles]

08:53.367 --> 08:55.033
(Lisa)
Just my closet.

08:55.068 --> 08:56.368
(Gordon)
Holy crap.

08:56.403 --> 08:57.802
- Stop it.
- Yeah.

08:57.838 --> 08:59.237
- Stop it?
- Seriously?

08:59.273 --> 09:00.972
(Lisa)
All my stuff.

09:01.008 --> 09:02.974
(Gordon)
It's like a garage sale
in a closet.

09:03.010 --> 09:04.809
(Lisa)
That's why we keep
a lock on it.

09:04.845 --> 09:06.211
I've got no interest
in wearing any of the garments,

09:06.246 --> 09:07.479
but thank you.

09:07.514 --> 09:09.147
- You sure?
- I'm positive.

09:09.182 --> 09:10.749
100% positive.

09:10.784 --> 09:13.084
Bloody hell.

09:13.120 --> 09:14.953
- What's the price of this room?
- This one is $220.

09:14.988 --> 09:18.056
- $220, yeah?
- Correct.

09:18.091 --> 09:20.859
And I have to share my wardrobe
with the owner.

09:20.894 --> 09:22.794
What's through this room here?

09:22.829 --> 09:24.496
That actually goes
to my bedroom.

09:24.531 --> 09:27.432
So do you just walk in when
you need to get some clothes?

09:27.467 --> 09:29.000
From here?

09:29.036 --> 09:30.936
No, but from your bedroom
to my bedroom.

09:30.971 --> 09:32.837
Well, I only do that
once or twice a week.

09:34.875 --> 09:37.275
And what's this?

09:37.311 --> 09:38.543
Wow.

09:38.579 --> 09:39.978
It's an antique purse

09:40.013 --> 09:41.580
that was actually found
in the house,

09:41.615 --> 09:44.316
and we thought it was
really neat to be able to have.

09:44.351 --> 09:46.518
That's for--
that's a toothbrush holder

09:46.553 --> 09:48.954
in case you decide
to take it along with you.

09:48.989 --> 09:50.488
That's a toothbrush holder?

09:50.524 --> 09:53.224
Or you could stick tampons in
there if you really wanted to.

09:53.260 --> 09:54.993
We do usually have those--

09:55.028 --> 09:56.494
Oh, they're not in there
right now.

09:56.530 --> 09:57.996
- There you go.
- It's an old lady's case.

09:58.031 --> 10:00.098
Mm-hmm, just trying
to think of clever ideas

10:00.133 --> 10:03.168
to make this feel
like a historic inn.

10:03.203 --> 10:04.903
Historic.

10:04.938 --> 10:06.871
- Mm.
- It's definitely historic.

10:06.907 --> 10:08.273
Oh.

10:08.308 --> 10:09.908
Bloody hell.
How old is that?

10:09.943 --> 10:11.443
You need that?

10:11.478 --> 10:13.178
No, just fascinated
to see what's in my basket.

10:13.213 --> 10:15.647
Thank you for that.
Oh, dear.

10:15.682 --> 10:17.415
Everything looks dated.

10:17.451 --> 10:20.051
I mean, first impressions--
it looks very, very tired.

10:20.087 --> 10:22.020
What is all that?

10:22.055 --> 10:24.055
That's if somebody wants
to throw roses on the bed.

10:24.091 --> 10:25.190
Oh, for God's sake.

10:25.225 --> 10:26.458
Isn't that adorable?

10:26.493 --> 10:28.960
And then they go back
in the drawer...

10:28.996 --> 10:30.629
- I guess so.
- Once you've used them.

10:33.233 --> 10:35.400
Okay, well, I'll look forward
to seeing you downstairs.

10:35.435 --> 10:36.701
- I'll have lunch.
- Super.

10:36.737 --> 10:39.304
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

10:39.339 --> 10:41.206
Wow.

10:41.241 --> 10:43.241
[bleep].

10:43.276 --> 10:45.310
That's freaky.

10:45.345 --> 10:48.213
The owner's bedroom
is literally a meter away.

